Yeah I know I’m a nobody with just 1 self-published novel under my belt, but I’m also a reader. Readers are who we are telling this story to, not editors, not publishers. Tell that story however you want them to hear it.
@NouhBdee I literally just post a long-ass thread about this, and you summed it all up in one tweet!
@NouhBdee EXACTLY!

It is a subconscious visual cue and, like I said, it continues momentum. You can convey big feelings, draw the reader in, and help them feel the story as you wish it to be felt. It is not “redundant” as those articles say. The ! has its purpose. Figure out how you want to use it.

And it goes beyond dialogue. Which version do you think is more solemn/resigned? Which more panicked and desperate?

That was it. He was done for.

That was it! He was done for!
And that fluidity has a purpose. It immerses the reader. There is no nano-second double take to trip up the reader’s flow, and their imagination can continue to unfold.

Let’s try it again.

“And now I can’t find my other shoe!” she barked.

My guess is you already knew how that line was to be read with much less disconnect, correct? You may not have noticed it, but you saw that ! And were prepared for the voice to be sharp in some way.

Here is a sentence. Read it, please.

“That’s it. I’m through,” he bellowed.

Tell me, was there a pause in your brain? Did you read the dialogue quietly and then do a double-take, realizing it was a bellow?

A very very hazy memory rose to the surface of my brain while I enjoyed some time with Dr. Teal. I think it was my 9th grade creative writing teacher. We were coving punctuation, and she said punctuation is a tool to keep thought and momentum going.

Neighbor toddlers cried, kids took pictures, and my sister and her boyfriend learned a very valuable lesson. Never use beets for snow people eyes.

Outside they see their cute snowman looking far more sinister. The melting snowman’s beet eyes were gone, leaving gaping bloody eye sockets. The tootsie rolls had fallen enough to look like fangs, and he was slumped forward with menacing claws ready for snatching.
Then, during the night, it warmed up and the snow started melting, and in the morning they heard people reacting strangely. They peeked outside to see what the hubbub was all about.

After scrounging, they cut an old beet in half for eyes, and made a smile out of mini tootsie rolls. An odd looking snowman, but he was cute and friendly with big happy eyes and stick-arms ready for hugs.
Being childless adults at the time, they didn’t exactly have all the necessary pieces. They had sticks for arms and a carrot nose, but had to get creative.
The year is 2003 (approximately). My sister is at her boyfriend’s house and just got the first major snowfall of the season. Excited, the lovebirds decided to make a snowman.

Honestly I don’t even know where I’m going with this. I’m just mad. The romance genre is the biggest money-maker in the publishing world, and I’d like to see it get the respect it so rightfully deserves.

I don’t even know where to begin with the misogyny, homophobia, and racism already attached to these negative stereotypes of the genre. Believe it or not, poc, lgbtqia, and straight men also enjoy reading and writing romance, and they shouldn’t be made to feel bad about it.
You’re not reading something “emotionally engaging”. Who cares if the protagonist is, like you, a survivor of abuse and/or trauma? It’s just “socially-acceptable porn for women”
And it’s a shame, because it all boils back down to, well, shame. Shame to be caught reading such “drivel”. It’s not a complex narrative about love and self-discovery. It’s a “trashy romance novel”
Sure, there are plenty of bodice-rippers out there (and those are fantastic too), but there are so many subgenres and niches that go completely untouched by those outside of romance-readers.

I have so many thoughts and feelings in regards to the romance/erotica genres still being boiled down to (and written off as) “porn for bored housewives”. And what’s even more infuriating is that I’m not saying anything new. Stop looking down on these genres.
